Food to blame for European inflation
The main reason for the increase in inflation measured in the eurozone is the rapid rise in food prices.
In the 13 countries of the eurozone, the inflation rate was higher than expected in November - after the 2.6 percent in October, an annual inflation rate of 3.1 percent was recorded, according to the EU Statistical Office in Luxembourg.
Official forecasts are only 3 percent, Bloomberg reported.
Unlike the American, British and Canadian central banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) has not lowered the Leitzsins. In its discretion, the interest rate cut would favour the rise in commodity prices and the slight fall in unemployment to the emergence of an inflationary spiral.
The ECB strives to keep the inflation rate below two percent, or at least close to the two percent mark.
According to an analyst, the ECB is in the midst of a twilight: inflation must be “agreed” in order to rule out the need for action later on.
At 3.3 percent, the inflation rate reached a twelve-year record high in Germany in November; in Spain, the rate climbed from 3.6 to 4.1 percent.
The reason for the rise in inflation in the eurozone is the rise in food and energy prices.
The MATIF wheat quotations rose by 88 percent, and the price of soybeans also reached a record high since 1973.
In 2007, there was also a significant increase in the price of cooking oil and dairy products.
The world market price for crude oil rose by 52 percent this year – last month the price per barrel of black gold reached nearly 100 US dollars.
According to the ECB, inflation will rise from 2.1 percent to 2.5 percent in 2008, but it is expected to fall to 1.9 percent in 2009.
For the next 3-4 months, analysts expect a 3-percent inflation rate, but the annual average rate is 2.1 percent.
For 2008, experts expect the ECB to cut interest rates twice.
Gallup instigates government crisis
After a long stagnation, the number of Fidesz sympathizers has grown considerably until the beginning of December. For the first time since 2002, the party has the largest base camp, while the approval for the socialists has reached an unprecedented low of 13 percent, according to Gallup.
The difference among the party-faithful voters is clear thanks to the high determination of the opposition supporters: More than two-thirds (71 percent) are opposed to a fifth (20 percent) approval for the MSZP.
According to the survey, MDF and SZDSZ are below the parliamentary entry hurdle: they reach two percent of the total population.
The number of party voters has grown by one percent in both camps.
Compared to the last low, the overall economic mood has continued to deteriorate - never before has the proportion of those who judge the country's economic situation as "extremely bad" been so high (41 percent), while another 46 percent consider it to be "quite bad".
After more hopeful prospects in spring and summer, families see the change in their financial situation again more pessimistic.
For the coming year, the majority of the population expects a further deterioration of the situation; only one tenth expects an improvement.
A Gallup survey conducted in December found that 71% of respondents – a historic high – rated the Prime Minister’s work as “rather bad than right.”
Thirteen percent of the respondents have great trust or confidence in Ferenc Gyurcs<0xC3><0xA1>ny in general, while the proportion of supporters for Viktor Orb<0xC3><0xA1>n accounts for 38 percent.
About 54% do not trust the head of government at all, compared to 27% distrust of the Fidesz party leader.
One of the indicators of political sentiment is the number of people who think that they can cope with dissatisfaction with the Prime Minister even without a change of government.
If, after the unrest in October last year, 35% had voted for the remainder of the government and the head of government, that share today amounts to only 20%, while the relative majority (33 percent) sees the solution only in new elections.
Asked about their interest in the referendum, 60 percent responded that they would “participate with certainty” and another 20 percent would “probably” cast their vote.
By way of comparison, if the parliamentary elections were to take place this Sunday, only 55 percent would go to the polls "with certainty" and another 15 percent would consider their participation "probable", given these trends, the result of the referendum would be foreseeable.
74% would vote against the tuition fees, 79% against the practice fee, and 84% would vote against the hospital daily allowance.
Turning to the group of participants in the referendum "with certainty", the proportion of opponents of the study, practice and hospital fees would be even 81, 84, and 89 percent, respectively.
