In many places, disinfectants are saved
This year, more than a thousand infections were registered in hospitals due to improper use of antibiotics.
The hygienic conditions in the hospitals, the overcrowding of the beds, the overload of the staff - all factors that do not exactly contribute to the containment of infections, according to the senior physician of the National Epidemiology Center.
In many places, disinfectants are also saved.
The traumatology department of the J<0xC3><0xA1>nos Hospital has recently been diagnosed with an MRSA infection.
The antibiotic-resistant bacterium was found in a male patient who was hospitalized after a serious accident.
The patient was isolated.
At the beginning of the year, there was a similar infection.
The victim of a serious car accident was discharged from the hospital, but soon afterwards the man had to return with an MRSA infection. An important operation could not be performed since because of the bacterium, which is still in the patient's body.
By December 10 this year, 1094 infections caused by multi-resistant pathogens were reported from hospitals to the National Nosocomialis Surveillance System, according to the senior physician of the National Epidemiology Center, Karolina Böröcz.
So many infections caused by multi-resistant pathogens have certainly been registered in hospitals, but the dark figure is likely to be higher.
About two-thirds of infections (683 cases) were triggered by MRSA, Staphylococcus aureus resistant to methicillin-oxacillin.
The Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacterium carries about one-third of the people in its nose without causing a disease.
SA-related infections (such as sore throat, tonsillitis, inflammation of the skin or wounds) usually respond well to antibiotics, they are well curable.
However, if the agents are overdosed or improperly used, the well-reacting bacteria produce antibiotic-resistant bacteria that spread rapidly in hospitals under appropriate conditions.
Especially in patients with weakened, or permanently poorly functioning immune system, but also in older, or patients with low body weight, these bacteria can cause serious infections, such as wound infection or blood poisoning, i.e. sepsis.
According to the medical director of the J<0xC3><0xA1>nos Hospital, the MRSA infection is nothing special, such incidents are part of everyday hospital life.
The infection should not be confused with the epidemic, Tibor Nyulasi warned - MRSA only does not exist where it is not sought.
Resistant to antibiotics
"Such patients are isolated, caregivers wear rubber gloves and masks during care, and we have the antibiotics necessary for treatment," says Tibor Nyulasi.
While patients are being examined for MRSA when they are admitted to the hospital, infection cannot always be avoided.
Sampling too rare
The majority of infections caused by MRSA in hospitals would be avoidable, but the current conditions and circumstances are unfavourable for curbing the development or spread of the multi-resistant pathogen, says Karolina Böröcz.
After this infection occurs predominantly in hospitals and retirement homes, hospitals should examine the patients enrolled and isolate MRSA-infected patients immediately.
However, microbiological sampling is not practiced so frequently in Hungarian hospitals.
Not least because there are no grants from the state health insurance company for this investigation.
Most cases therefore only come to light when the patient already has a noticeable MRSA infection, according to the medical director of the epidemiology center.
There are strict recommendations from the European Union on the appropriate use of antibiotics in human medicine, but there are also guidelines in Hungary for the treatment of certain infections and diseases.
Antibiotic therapies should be targeted, that is, microbiological examinations are necessary to prevent resistance to the drug, but this directive is not always observed by hospitals.
Among the outpatient or primary care patients, microbiological sampling is even rarer, says Karolina Böröcz.
Saved by disinfectants
Scientific evidence shows that MRSA is most commonly transmitted from one patient to another by nursing staff.
It is precisely for this reason that hand washing or wearing gloves and masks is of great importance, but there are also significant deficiencies in the hospitals in this area.
MRSA is transmitted by droplet infection or contact, but in domestic hospitals there is not always the possibility of isolating the infected patient.
The rooms are even often crowded, the beds are tightly lined, although from an epidemiological point of view there should be a distance of at least 1.5 meters between them.
As Karolina Böröcz further notes, unfortunately, in the financially less well-positioned hospitals it even happens that disinfectants are saved, there are few caregivers, many patients - all factors that actually favor the development of infections.
Such infections are demonstrably far less common there, or the further spread of the pathogen can be stopped where these protective measures are observed, according to Karolina Böröcz.
Government program against MRSA
Getting to grips with MRSA infections causes the health insurance companies enormous costs, so they are combated everywhere.
In England, for example, the prevention of MRSA or its containment was recorded in the government program.
After first signs, the program is successful - as published data shows, the trend of MRSA infections in England is declining.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention (ECDC) has declared the prevention of the development of multi-resistant pathogens (including MRSA) and the prevention of infections in hospitals as one of its priorities.
