Bulgaria, the real estate paradise of the EU
The development of the Bulgarian real estate market is fabulous - all of Europe is attentive to the previously rarely mentioned Balkan state.
What, where, and who buys the EU’s still cheapest market, but which is rapidly becoming more expensive?
An analysis of the Bulgarian Re/Max Division.
Bulgaria is undoubtedly the most sought-after pavement for real estate purchases in Eastern Europe, with affordable ski apartments and houses by the sea.
Between the mountains, the regions of Bansko, Borovec, Pamprovo and Vitosa are among the most popular, by the sea are Albena, the "Gold Coast", the "Sun Coast", and the historic towns of Sozopol and Nessebar the racers, but real estate around Kavarna and Balcik are also increasingly in demand.
According to estimates by Re/Max analysts in Bulgaria, the interior of the country sooner or later attracts investors, such as Veliko Tarnovo, Gabrovo, Elena, and Triavna, and also the extremely favorable area of Russia has more buyers.
The capital Sofia also offers tempting offers - commercial and office space offer the highest returns.
Bulgaria is on its way to becoming one of the most attractive European golfers’ paradises, attracting tourists in both the summer and winter seasons.
Forward-looking investors are already purchasing on a large scale, for example around Bansko.
According to analysts, people who purchase real estate in Bulgaria also seek to change their way of life.
Most buyers are English, but there are also interested parties from France, Belgium, Spain, and more and more from Romania.
Investors from Malta and Cyprus are also present, while there are mainly Russian buyers at the Black Sea and in the ski resorts.
There are three groups of foreign buyers, says Georgij Jankov, Regional Director of Re/Max Bulgaria.
Those who want to settle down, either buy revitalized properties by 50-100,000 euros, or run-down houses by 5-15,000 euros, which they then renovate themselves.
Good connectivity and accessibility as well as communication options are important, but also the proximity to a big city, shops and doctors are crucial for the buyers.
The second category includes those who are looking for a holiday home (Bulgaria was listed among the top ten holiday destinations of the Germans in December).
The third group is made up of business people who invest with the aim of increasing value in the medium to long term.
However, real estate in the capital is becoming increasingly expensive due to the ever-increasing demand.
Within the EU, property prices are lowest in Bulgaria, but in the past five years there has been a price increase of 21 percent annually.
The cost of real estate prices far exceeds the increase in salaries.
Fodor and the Six Hungarian Percentages
As Environment Minister G<0xC3><0xA1>bor Fodor announced, the expert meetings will end on Tuesday, and the debate on the international climate regime after 2012 will continue by ministers on Wednesday after the official opening.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries are discussing the Bali Roadmap, which sets out the emission-reducing measures for the period after 2012, i.e. after the end of the Kyoto Protocol.
There is currently a fierce debate between developed and developing countries.
The U.S. has already signaled that it does not want to negotiate concrete figures, but would be willing to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 25-40% by 2020 compared to 1990.
The other big question of the conference is whether the developed countries are willing to support developing countries both financially and technologically, in addition to reducing emissions.
An agreement on aid to developing countries has also been reached.
The Adaptation Fund under the Kyoto Protocol is to be managed by a 16-member Council, expected to be implemented at the UN’s Global Environmental Facility (GEF), as can be read in the “Piac és Profit”.
Hungary's 6%
On behalf of Hungary, Environment Minister G<0xC3><0xA1>bor Fodor supports the EU’s commitment to maintain its leading role in global climate action and to achieve a new international agreement by 2009.
The Minister said that the EU would reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 20% by 2020 (measured by the 1990 levels) regardless of whether or not the "after-2012 agreement" will be successfully achieved, and that the Union would even be prepared to commit to a 30 percent reduction if other major industrialised countries in the world, or developing countries, are also willing to fulfil their obligations to their fullest and responsibly.
G<0xC3><0xA1>bor Fodor stressed that the objective of the countries that had joined the Kyoto Protocol in 1997 was a reduction of only 5.2 percent, whereas the EU with its then 15 member states had already committed itself to a reduction of 8%.
The requirement for Hungary is to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 6% compared to 1985-87 - a requirement that the country will certainly meet, as can be read in the press release of the Ministry of the Environment.
The commitment is high on Bali - after all, the long-term international climate agreement must be completed within two years, otherwise it would certainly not come into force until after 2012. In this case, the reduction project set out in the Kyoto Protocol would not follow a new, international emission reduction system whose importance has also been highlighted by the IPCC, the international scientific climate change committee which has been awarded the Nobel Peace Prize in its recent report.
This would delay the emission reduction, and increasing the Earth’s average temperature by more than 2°C would be unavoidable, which, according to scientists, would have extremely serious and irreparable consequences.
British Army advertises on YouTube
Units of the British Army have published footage of operations in Iraq and Afghanistan for the purpose of increasing popularity on the video portal.
First, the British Air Force (RAF) has discovered YouTube for itself: Special forces stationed in Afghanistan have been uploading videos of operations against the Taliban on the net since March 2006, the BBC reports.
The images made with miniature cameras attached to helmets are monitored at the Air Force base in Kandahar and then sent to London, where they are put on the Internet.
Political message unavoidable
Air Force soldiers have already contributed 139 such recordings, their "channel" has been viewed more than 75,000 times.
The British Department of Defense was registered under "defence headquarters" in spring 2007 to publish videos of Iraqi and Afghan operations, but also the British Foreign Ministry (Commonwealth Office) and the international peacekeeping forces (MNFI) stationed in Iraq have their own YouTube channels.
Operations in Afghanistan
Originally, the Air Force released the videos with the aim of recruiting soldiers, and, as the Ministry of Defense says, the contributions also serve the purpose of informing the population about the actual goals of foreign operations.
Such published propaganda is almost free compared to conventional television advertisements, according to defense expert Gordon Mackenzie to the BBC, but these videos always carry a certain amount of political message, as they confirm the existence of the military measures decided by the government in their own way.
Americans Advertise with Game
But the army must also fight against amateur shots, which, in addition to the carefully edited, censored shots, also make it into the net - such as those that show the death of the soldiers: In the somewhat hypocritical, "official" propaganda films, the losses are talked about at most, but the bloody sides of the war are not shown.
By the way, numerous videos shot during the war in Iraq and Afghanistan have already been uploaded to the platform, but the British have only recently discovered this "gender" for themselves.
The Americans, however, advertise in a slightly different way, namely with the free downloadable shooting game "America's Army", in which the player can slip into the skin of the soldier as part of a more or less lifelike simulation.
