Political Capital: Hungarian Guard increases state risk
According to the Risk Analysis Division of Political Capital, the activities of the Hungarian Guard, founded this August with the support of the "Movement for a Better Hungary", have increased the risk of Hungary and the region in several ways.
The Institute's "Risk Warning Report" states, among other things, that in connection with the activities of the Hungarian Guard, the highest political risk is the "intensification of the already existing ethnic tensions between the gypsies and non-gypsy population in Hungary, which could even lead to violent ethnic conflicts in the short term".
The main reason for this is the strategy of the Hungarian Guard, which is presumably aimed at provoking such a dispute, according to the research institute.
As reported, this is seen as a failure on the part of the political leaders: "Persons of public life have left the discussion of the Roma question to representatives of radical political groups who have now built their political strategy on the Roma-Hungary opposition."
It is believed that this would exacerbate the problem, make reasonable dialogue impossible, favor extremities, and increase the likelihood of violent conflicts.
The research institute also believes that the activities of the Hungarian Guard, not least thanks to the enormous attention of the domestic and foreign media, "had significantly damaged Hungary's image abroad, especially in terms of confidence in stability and democratic maturity".
We remember: Since autumn 2006, the reorganization of radical and extreme right-wing groups in Hungary has been continuously on the rise, so that since summer 2007 several organisations, called "national self-defense associations", have been founded.
“These groups have in common that they each define themselves as a civilian organization, while openly bragging about preparing their members for – sometimes armed – defense tasks (catastrophe protection, state defense, order guarding), citing the inability of the police, the army, or the state itself,” it said.
And furthermore, all this is done according to the method that attempts to disguise various political aspirations, based on the political and party resentment of the population, as a bourgeois initiative.
The emphasis on the civil character and the form of the association, therefore, do not merely serve to circumvent legal hurdles that could arise in the course of registration with the court - it is at the same time a political strategy.
As can be seen from the analysis, the activities of the Hungarian Guard are also a risk-increasing factor for relations with neighbouring countries.
"In recent months, the Hungarian Guard has been cited as a potential source of danger in several neighbouring states, as some ultranationalist politicians of certain neighbouring countries see in the emergence of the Hungarian Guard the confirmation of its own anti-Hungarian policy.
All of this has an impact on the political stability of the region," he said.
