Holidays are not holidays everywhere
In Hungary, public holidays are strictly regulated by law, so that the practice of rescheduling the working days around the public holidays has now become established, but next year gives us less such days.
Also in the EU and in America, something else is understood as "holiday".
The Hungarian legal system distinguishes between state holidays and non-working days.
Unemployment-free days are usually church holidays, or are related to significant historical events.
For example, we also celebrate New Year: both the last day of the old and the first day of the new year are work-free days - the latter alone so that the New Year's Eve celebrations can rest.
We have a total of 14 holidays throughout the year.
The National Holidays are March 15, commemorating the Revolution of 1848, and October 23, commemorating the Revolution of 1956.
On the 20th of August, the founding of the state, on the 1st of May the work is celebrated, on the 1st and 2nd of November we commemorate our dead.
In addition, there are two holidays each at Easter, Pentecost, and Christmas.
Since our state, national or religious holidays rarely fall on a weekend, the practice of "workday shift" has proven itself in cases where we would only work one day before or after the holiday.
The price of the extended weekends, however, is that we have to work very well on the Saturdays before, or go to school.
When this day, which falls before or after the holiday, will ultimately be processed, has long been determined by the Minister of Labour in his own regulation.
The legislation applies to all employers and beneficiaries, to public servants and civil servants alike.
Excluded are only companies and facilities in which the operation is continued without interruption, i.e. also on the holidays.
At the end of the year, the working order is only somewhat confused by the holidays: From 24 December, life in this country remains formally standing, since most of the days between Christmas and New Year's Eve take time compensation, or the specially canceled holiday.
In the next year, more holidays fall in the middle of the week, or at the end of the week, so there will be fewer redistributions on working days than this year.
The calendar is first "turned upside down" around the day of work, so that people can stay at home for four days at a time.
Saturday, April 26 will be a working day so that Friday, May 2 can be a rest day.
The second rescheduling is related to the holiday on 23 October: on Saturday, 18 October, you will have to work out the Friday, 24 October in advance.
However, the end of the year will be completely in the focus of the holidays, after everything will lie and stand, even if New Year’s Eve falls on a Wednesday.
Six deterrent little things to annoy colleagues
E-mails that we forget to send, voice messages that we never receive - harmless lies that we no longer notice: they bring "color" into everyday work.
The only question is whether you get used to these little inconveniences, or do you better face the challenge and try to avoid these misunderstandings, consciously for other annoying situations.
Tips.
“Sorry, I forgot to point you out that someone called from the marketing department,” says one colleague.
Did you miss a meeting?
At best, you regret it and try to make up for it by perhaps calling the marketing department and repentantly confessing that you forgot to align the message (this is the less common method).
Most of the time, the issue is dismissed with an apology.
Before you get caught up in embarrassing excuses, think about what you can do to give your colleagues truly unpleasant moments and try to consciously avoid these situations.
Borrow something that doesn’t belong to you?
There’s hardly anything more annoying than grabbing a document, office accessories, or the phone, but it’s not there.
Yesterday the stapler was still on the desk - this morning it's gone?
Or is the lost ballpoint pen discovered on a colleague’s desk?
Without questions, you should not borrow from colleagues, because they are rightly upset when they find that something has gone away.
So, don't put envelopes or post-it out of the office in your pocket, because it could hit you yourself: no more if you urgently need it.
Talking about the private life of colleagues?
There is no effective way to stop a gossip that has already been put into the world.
Who with whom, what did you do?
Where and why?
You should not tie the information (or assumptions) about the private life of colleagues to everyone's nose if possible!
And if anyone opens up and reveals his inner secret to us, we should not abuse this trust!
It is best to remain silent like a grave, instead of directing those who are not present, even if others know about the problems of the colleague.
Reported sick for no reason?
If you call in the office to report sickly, citing painful headaches, because you are feeling uncomfortable, or just want to rest, you should be aware of one thing: your own work, indefinite completions, projects with fixed appointments must now be done by the colleagues instead of yourself.
Don’t play badly with your colleagues.
If you already know the day before that you will not make it to the office the next day, or that something could come in between, which is why you have to stay at home, you should report it in time so that neither the colleagues nor the boss are unexpectedly confronted with the absence.
In other words, phone calls, phone calls
One is just deepened in his work, but is suddenly disturbed by the loud giggle of the colleagues?
Unintentionally listening to a phone call that you shouldn’t have heard?
You should not annoy your colleagues with buzzing, singing, loud conversations (which are carried over their heads), kicking, constant scorn or nagging.
All of this can be very disturbing, even if they are not exactly immersed in a task (writing, planning, organizing).
Are the others always to blame?
If a project is not finished on time, you have forgotten to send an important letter or important messages, you should not look for the guilt of your own forgetfulness with others!
If possible, you should not talk about the chaos in the office or the noisy colleagues!
It’s best to acknowledge your mistakes, and apologize if others were affected!
The question of how to make up for the mistake or make up for the missing is all too appropriate!
In the office - a feeling like at home?
Training pants and slippers: Comfortable for at home, but hasn't lost anything in the office!
Not even then should you dress so casually if the workplace would actually allow it!
Just don't get too sloppy - you should respect both your colleagues and yourself to the extent that you dress appropriately in the office - if desired, also pretty and elegant!
