The US Federal Reserve, the European Central Bank and the central banks of the UK, Switzerland and Canada have decided to fight together against the crisis in the financial markets.
For example, more than $100 billion will reach the currency markets through auctions.
On these auctions, banks are auctioning interest rates at which they are willing to lend each other money.
For example, the U.S. Fed is sending $40 billion to auction, with another 24 making it loose for the European and Swiss central banks.
This is the first time that the central banks of the individual states have agreed on such a coordinated approach to mitigate or mitigate the consequences of a financial crisis.
“This step is intended to eliminate the biggest difficulties of the economy, i.e. the growing lack of freely available capital that banks can lend,” wrote Bernard Baumohl of Economic Outlook Group.
“The coordinated action of central banks has reduced the likelihood of a recession in the U.S. from 65% to about 50%,” Baumohl added in his report.
The banks have already lost $60 billion due to unserviced loans, especially in the United States.
Analysts expect billions more losses.
“Central banks must have been really afraid of what could happen if they decided to do this,” said Kieran Davies, chief economist at ABN Amro.
"It looks like the situation is really bad," he continued.
Central banks fear that if banks themselves have difficult access to bonds, loans will also become more expensive for their customers.
This would reduce consumption and plunge the American economy into a recession, possibly affecting economic growth around the world.
The central banks have decided to do so after failing to lower the so-called LIBOR, the London interbank interest rate used in lending money between banks.
This means that the banks were constantly afraid of lending each other money, even though the central banks of the US, Canada and the UK had lowered their interest rates several times during the fall.
