Cuba - the most beautiful island in the Caribbean
For visitors, it is truly an island of freedom.
Whatever you expect from your holiday, it will come true if you choose just the right one.
Golden and white beaches, high waves or a sea that is calm like a pond.
Palms and all-inclusive with waiters offering pizza, ice cream and captivating cocktails on the beach.
Kitesurfing, golf and roulette.
On the islands of the Caribbean you will find this in an abundant amount.
But only on one island you will find much more, and this island is Cuba, the largest and most beautiful of the Greater Antilles.
At the time of the Spaniards, Cuba was their bastion for the conquest of America.
Columbus called it the most beautiful place a human eye has ever seen.
Havana once became a warehouse or transit warehouse of treasures that the Spaniards had robbed in America and then transported to Europe.
And then came the American era.
The Hotel Nacional was built at the end of the 20th century.
It was built by one of the chiefs of the American mafia, Lucky Luciano, because everything that was considered a crime in the U.S. (especially during Prohibition) was seen and supported in Cuba - drugs, gambling, prostitution.
Among his guests were, among other things,
Winston Churchill, Ava Gardner, Frank Sinatra.
In Havana, high-rise buildings grew, and cars drove across the wide boulevards, which were among the cult symbols of the fifties of the last century.
Ernest Hemingway bought a property in San Francisco de Paula, near Havana, and in Coj<0xC3><0xAD>mar he had his yacht laid.
On the walls of the Bodeguita del Medio, show business stars and politicians from all over America left their signatures.
And today?
You can also leave your autograph on the walls of the Bodeguita of Havana.
At the bar at the Hotel Nacional you can mix cocktails according to your wishes.
And the cult cars of the fifties still drive around Havana to this day, because the once imported shigulis and fiats have long since fallen apart in the salty and humid air.
May Havana, especially its oldest part, have fallen down sharply, nowhere in the vicinity you will find as many wonderful colonial sights as here.
Other places are currently being cleaned out, for example Trinidad.
In view of the fact that tourism brings much needed money, there was a green light for this development.
In the last fifteen years, new hotels have emerged not only in Havana, but also in Varadero, on the coast of the province of Holgu<0xC3><0xAD>n and also on islets such as Cayo Coco, Cayo Guillermo and others.
Cuba also offers a marmot that is unique in the world and attracts railway enthusiasts.
The sugar cane from remote plantations brought steam- and diesel-driven narrow-gauge railways to the sugar factories.
Their fleet has not been renewed for decades, and so you can see neat and fully functioning locomotives, whose peers are already elsewhere in the museum.
Excursion destinations
The most important places do not leave out the majority of visitors to Cuba.
So you don't have to write about Varadero or Havana in detail anymore.
It is worth mentioning that there is a museum in Hemingway’s already mentioned estate, whose visit should not be missed by the person who likes this writer.
The Vi<0xC3><0xB1>ales Valley to the west of the island is one of the most picturesque corners of Cuba.
The lush vegetation grows on lime soil.
The mogotas, limestone hills and rocks, rise steeply from the valley floor, in their cavities fertile soils accumulated, through which also weathered rock areas are covered by dense vegetation.
This valley is where perhaps the best Cuban tobacco is grown.
In its final form you can meet him when you visit one of the cigar factories of Havana.
It may also seem interesting to some that the Chilean episode of the TV series "Major Zeman" was filmed there.
Trinidad (disambiguation)
An ancient city that was founded shortly after the Spaniards had colonized the island.
The trade in slaves and sugar brought her fame and wealth.
The wealth was embodied in the beautiful beauty of the small town.
Spanish colonial architecture, strongly influenced by the later French settlers, has hardly changed for four hundred years.
Trinidad, located between the sea and the Escambray Mountains, is such a remote place that in the fifties of the last century there was no road there that would have connected the area with the rest of the country.
This isolation helped to keep it unnoticed.
Nothing was built there, but nothing was torn down, everyone was glad that he had a roof over his head.
If you have more than an afternoon for Trinidad, it is worth seeing interesting places in the area, such as Playa Anc<0xC3><0xB3>n beach or the "Valley of Sugar Factory".
In the evening you should go to the Casa de la M<0xC3><0xBA>sica, which revitalizes after darkness, and where the music does not remain silent until the morning.
Baracoa
This small town in the east of Cuba is considered by some to be the most beautiful of the island.
Certainly, this view is also influenced by the way there.
Both roads leading there from Guant<0xC3><0xA1>namo have to overcome high and rugged mountains and run through a landscape that is barely touched by human intervention.
UNESCO included this eastern outpost of Cuba in its World Heritage List thanks to its pristine nature.
There, the best chocolate is made, in the church you can see the cross of Columbus (in fact it originated about a hundred years after the journeys of Columbus), and from the hill where the former castle, the present Hotel El Castillo, stands, you can see several table mountains, of which El Yunque is the most famous.
About coffee, rum, cigars, Sierra Maestra mountains, the Bay of Pigs and the Island of Isla de Pinos, about the Tropicana cabaret, the Sanctuary of Cuban patron Caridad del Cobre, about the Santeria, an African religion to which the descendants of slaves profess, could be written on many pages about all this.
But, as they say, it is better to look with your own eyes.
