For giving a name to a teddy bear, she was presented to a court in Khartoum today.
According to her lawyer, the British teacher, who had been charged in Sudan for insulting Islam, was sentenced on Thursday evening by a court in Khartoum to 15 days imprisonment and subsequent expulsion.
The British was accused of allowing six- to seven-year-old students to give a teddy bear the name Mahomet, although any depiction of the Islamic prophet is prohibited.
She deserved to be whipped.
After parents of students complained to the Sudanese Ministry of Culture several times, the 54-year-old elementary school teacher working at the Unity High School of Khartoum was picked up at home on Sunday and accused of insulting Islam under Article 125 of the Sudanese Penal Code.
In fact, this matter begins in September, when the teacher asks her six- to seven-year-old students to choose a name for the class teddy.
The children propose eight names, including Hassan, Abdullah and Mohammed, reports school principal Robert Boules.
Finally, when the class votes, 20 out of 23 children choose Mohammed as their favorite first name.
Certainly, Muhammad is the name of the Islamic prophet, but above all a very common first name in Sudan.
Afterwards, the children created a book for the class, with the photo of the bear on it and the caption My name is Mohammed.
The bear itself did not bear a sign bearing this name, but the problem is quite simple that the depiction of the Islamic prophet is seen as an insult to Islam.
One of the Muslim colleagues of Gillian Gibbons, who teaches at the same school in Sudan, explained that he knows her well, and she would never have done anything to make her too close to a religious faith, I only regret that she asked the children to vote for a name, in his opinion this is just an innocent mistake.
An opinion that many of the teacher’s students share, describing it as being very attentive to their students and as a person who never talks about religion in class.
Remember that the first name Mohammed is also the second most frequently given in the UK, for which there are 14 different spellings in English.
This name, often chosen by Muslim families, is considered a kind of reverence for the Prophet (he is often given to the firstborn of a family).
But what are the rules regarding the use of this first name?
Can you give it to a toy, for example?
This is, of course, a matter of interpretation.
On Wednesday, at the last negotiation meeting in Vienna, no agreement was reached on the future status of the province.
At the end of the failure
The Serbs and Albanians from Kosovo ended a sixth and final discussion in Baden, Austria, on Wednesday morning, without being able to overcome their controversy about the future status of the separatist province.
It is regrettable that the parties could not reach an agreement on the status, European mediator Wolfgang Ischinger explained at a press conference in Vienna.
Emphasizing that peace in the region is at stake, his American counterpart Frank Wilsner urged Belgrade and Pristina to comply with their commitments to maintain peace, and to continue the talks beyond the end of the negotiations.
No acts of violence are expected in the immediate future, but we are at the beginning of a very difficult time, he added, suggesting that there are quite clear tensions.
End of mediation on 10 December
The mediators of the Troika, which unites the European Union, the US and Russia, will meet one last time in Serbia and Kosovo on Monday.
The future of the province, which is 90% inhabited by Albanian speakers, could become clearer if Ischinger, Wilsner and the Russian mediator Alexander Botsane-Khartchenko submitted their report to the UN Security Council by December 10.
Baden’s talks, near Vienna, were the sixth and last negotiating session since the Troika had received the UN’s mandate for a new mediation last August.
Americans and Europeans expect their mediation contract to end on December 10.
The Russians, who had already blocked the granting of Kosovo’s independence to the Security Council, insist on a continuation of negotiations beyond this end date.
Russia has been and will continue to advocate a negotiated solution, a consensual solution, Botsane-Khartchenko said.
Unilateral Declaration of Independence?
After Kosovo has been under the administration of the UN for eight years, the Western countries consider independence under the supervision of the EU to be the only solution with a future.
Pristina is ready to proclaim them unilaterally if the Security Council does not decide in their favor.
Belgrade insists on greater autonomy
Unfortunately, no agreement could be reached, announced the President of the Autonomous Authority of Kosovo, Fatmir Sejdiu, at the Hotel in Baden, where since Monday these negotiations were held of last chance.
Hashim Thaci, former leader of the Kosovo rebellion and future prime minister of the province, shared his regrets.
However, he added that Belgrade’s proposed plan for autonomy is part of a past that has led to murders and deportations.
Domino effect
Serbian President Boris Tradic, for his part, was of the opinion that a compromise should always be sought, warning the Albanian majority from Kosovo of the consequences of a unilateral declaration of independence of the province.
Belgrade believes that it is particularly proving a “Domino effect” in a region so weakened by the wars of independence of the 1990s.
For Serbia, that does not mean that a compromise would be impossible, he said.
On Tuesday, the Serbian delegation insisted that any decision should be made solely in the Security Council, where its Russian ally has a veto right.
Kosovo's parliament will have the last word
Only one decision from the Security Council is acceptable for Serbia, Serbian Prime Minister Vojislav Kostunica said.
These negotiations took two years.
They must end as they began: in the Security Council.
Fatmir Sejdiu told journalists that Kosovo’s parliament will have the last word on status, adding that any unilateral declaration of independence will take place on the part of the Albanian-speaking population in coordination with the Western countries.
