New fears about natural gas dispute between Russia and Ukraine
There is a new price dispute between Ukraine and Russia, which increases the risk that Russian exports of fuel to Western Europe will be affected.
Most of Russia’s natural gas exports to the European Union (EU) are directed through Ukraine and any dispute between the two nations is closely monitored.
Kiev has warned that if Moscow raises the price it has to pay for natural gas, it will charge higher transit fees from Russia.
An earlier conflict between the two countries last year reduced deliveries to the EU countries.
The recent dispute between Kiev and Moscow is happening at a time when the Ukrainian government and the Russian state gas monopoly Gazprom are trying to reach an agreement on how much Ukraine has to pay for Russian natural gas in 2008.
According to Gazprom, Ukraine needs to be charged more, as the group has agreed to pay up to 50% additional for natural gas from neighboring Turkmenistan.
Analysts say this could mean Ukraine has to pay 40% more for Gazprom’s imports.
“It is important for us to use our arguments as one of the most important gas transit states in talks,” Ukraine’s Minister of Economy Anatoli Kinakh told Reuters.
"The changing natural gas prices should undoubtedly be linked to our arguments regarding the amount of transit fees [to Western Europe] via Ukraine."
In the last major natural gas dispute between Moscow and Kiev in January 2006, Gazprom cut deliveries to Ukraine.
This subsequently led to a fall in exports to Western Europe, which drastically increased prices.
Russian gas accounts for a quarter of the European Union’s supply.
Russia has the largest gas reserves in the world, but much of it remains underdeveloped.
As a result, Gazprom supplements its own supplies with gas from Turkmenistan and other Central Asian former Soviet nations.
NHS "must control foreign workers"
The Scottish State Health Service must improve the checks of criminal records for workers from outside Europe, said a member of the control body.
The recommendation of the chief financial controller Robert Black came after a foreign doctor in Scotland was brought in connection with the attack on Glasgow Airport in June.
Black also expressed concerns that the Scottish state health service does not have any precise ideas about the number of its foreign employees.
But his report pointed out that other important controls were carried out correctly in a sample of five health authorities.
The chief financial controller examined personnel recruited outside the European Economic Area as a result of the attack on Glasgow Airport.
Bilal Abdullah, 28, an Iraqi doctor at the Royal Alexandra Hospital in Paisley, was arrested at the airport after an SUV was driven through the doors of the main airport terminal.
He was one of three doctors who appeared in a video broadcast at Old Bailey in October, and was charged in connection with the alleged car bomb attack in the UK.
It is expected that the State Health Service will carry out checks in advance of hiring foreign employees to ensure that they have the necessary qualifications, experience and authorizations to work in the UK.
Although the health authorities use Disclosure Scotland to review criminal record records, the agency has no jurisdiction to obtain this information outside the UK.
The main auditor’s report now states, among other recommendations, that the board should pick up guidelines on the criminal record extract that helps employers with checks in different countries.
"Although we found evidence of these checks in some personnel records, they were not routinely carried out," the report noted.
Black said the Scottish health authorities would follow their pre-employment investigative guidelines to a high degree, but added: "Our report highlights areas where the system can be improved to ensure accurate information about the number of foreign health care workers is available."
BMA Scotland chairman Dr. Peter Terry said it was “extremely unlikely” that investigations prior to hiring potential NHS employees would identify people who could commit future terrorist attacks.
“The report says that current NHS Scotland pre-employment tests work well and it’s not clear what added value the recommendations will provide,” he said.
