Gordon Brown has discovered yet another pit to fall in; his way out of it remains the same.
For British scandals, this is not particularly slippery.
No noble titles seem to have been sold, no Parisian hotel bills paid by politicians, no extramarital toes being sucked.
But the discovery that a wealthy businessman has concealed donations to the British ruling Labour Party over more than 650,000 pounds ($1.3 million) over four years under the name of other people, and that the party has failed to report this, is something that would have been good without the contested Gordon Brown.
When, two months ago, the Prime Minister evaded the demand for an election to stupidly insult the intelligence of the British by claiming that opinion polls did not influence this decision, there was hope that he would offer a robust, efficient government.
Instead, as Vince Cable, the increasingly keen leader of the Liberal Democrats, put it, the once dreaded Brown has evolved from Stalin to Mr. Bean.
The unskillful rescue of Northern Rock, a troubled bank, showed regulatory weakness and poor judgment under fire.
Poorly thought-out proposals to amend tax laws have incited corporate associations against the government.
The tax-administration loss of personal data of 25 million people showed unimaginable administrative plucking.
A trio of retired generals launched an uprising in the upper house in protest against cuts in military spending: to be a minister of the armed forces, they claimed, was a part-time job.
Now there are the manifold donations of David Abrahams; Peter Watt, Labour’s Secretary General (and her former Chief Executive Officer) has already resigned.
None of this means that Brown irrevocably breaks up towards resignation.
Nevertheless, governments can reach a turning point after which they feel it is impossible to govern.
People do not like or trust politicians, but they usually withhold their skepticism when a new force takes office.
Once it is clear that it is unlikely that a prime minister will improve the situation, and he does not even need to be there for long, this delay is over: the public service is beginning to leak; the cabinet ministers are starting to chat; the press is looking for bad news; and the government is becoming defensive and aimless.
In a way, Brown’s position is particularly difficult because, unlike other political leaders, he cannot claim to be a new broom.
As much as he wanted to deny Tony Blair, he was his lieutenant-general.
The problems with Northern Rock and the tax jurisdiction documents, for example, are related to decisions made by Brown as Chancellor of the Treasury.
And even if he wasn’t directly involved in Blair’s misfortunes – as with the long “money for nobility” investigation of political party funding – voters may assume he was.
Still, Brown’s situation isn’t quite as bad as it looks.
The crimes are not as terrible as the Conservatives describe them.
As with Mr. Bean, no one has died, or been completely scammed.
And the antidote, painful as it may be, is to deliver what Brown’s naturally Stalinist tendencies have always promised: a reliable, solid and slightly brutal government.
The new attitude towards political donations is a good example.
The Garbosque Abraham, who compares his donations with his charitable gifts, says he does not wish public recognition for his benevolence.
This may be the case, but he did not have the choice.
The laws against anonymity for large political contributors are clear and they exist for a clear reason: the public has a right to know who can buy access to those who govern the country.
Watt, who says he knew about Abraham’s agreement, but not that it is illegal, will of course have to ask himself some questions; just like Jon Mendlesohn, Labour’s chief financial collector, who was told about the strange donations in October.
But so far, Brown hasn’t been involved: there’s nothing to suggest he knew about these confusions, even though most of the payments were made after his takeover in June.
So far, the Prime Minister has done half of the work.
He quickly condemned the violation of the laws by his party, but he diluted this determination by grasping a well-known instrument, a committee of inquiry on the subject - led to make the measure full, from a retired bishop and a judge.
In this case, the "learnings to be drawn from them" are not very complicated.
If the law is broken, it is a matter for the police.
Apart from that, there are other things Mr. Brown has to do, such as finding a permanent chairman for the independent Committee on Public Standards, which has been unoccupied for six months, and moving forward with a sweeping reform of political party funding.
This would require the hardliners of Labour to cooperate with the Conservatives and possibly abandon the special financial relationship with the unions – bitter pills for a party comrade like Mr. Brown.
But he should be aware of some biased facts.
Conservatives now have a clear lead in opinion polls; he has two years to win back voters; and the only way he can win is through unquestionable integrity and solid competence.
