Venus is the Earth's hellish twin
Despite its hostile atmosphere, Venus is more similar to Earth than previously thought: the European spacecraft "Venus Express" has detected lightning in the atmosphere and wind swirls on the poles, as they also occur on Earth in winter.
For nearly three decades, scientists have suspected that it is flashing on Venus.
Now, the European probe Venus Express has been able to detect electromagnetic waves at the edge of the atmosphere: the lightnings on Venus are shooting at an altitude of about 56 kilometers from cloud to cloud, reports Christopher Russel of the University of California in Los Angeles in the science magazine Nature.
According to the famous "Ursoup theory," lightning has created life on Earth: thunderstorms in the ocean are said to have stimulated reactions that led to the formation of amino acids, the building blocks of life.
Not so on Venus: "If there ever was life there, it must have been in very early history," explains Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution in Washington.
Today, there is hardly anything alive on the surface of Venus: the atmosphere is about a hundred times denser than on Earth, sometimes temperatures of 500 degrees.
"Venus may be the devil's twin of the Earth, but it's a twin," Russell said.
Why Venus, which is so similar to Earth in mass and size, has taken on such a completely different development, is the fundamental question of the ESA mission.
The launch of "Venus Express" in November 2005 was a milestone for Venus research, as since the early 1990s, no probe has been on its way to specifically explore this planet.
The latest research, which is now presented in several "Nature" articles, not only underscores the uniqueness of Venus within the solar system, according to the researchers.
"They also show that the similarities of our neighboring planet with the Earth are greater than initially assumed," the ESA said.
In addition to the already known whirlwind at the North Pole, the researchers also found a cloud strudel at the South Pole, which rotates much faster.
The phenomenon is reminiscent of air currents in the terrestrial winter hemisphere, writes a research team led by Giuseppe Piccioni of the Italian Istituto di Astrofisica Spaziale e Fisica Cosmica.
The second innermost planet of the solar system has almost the same mass as Earth and is nearly the same size with a diameter of 12,100 kilometers.
The planet, also known as the morning or evening star, orbits the sun in just under 225 days.
However, it revolves much more slowly around itself: a Venus day lasts 243 Earth days.
Although Venus, with surface temperatures of 460 degrees Celsius and a pressure of 92 bar, is hardly reminiscent of Earth, scientists assume that both planets originated under very similar conditions.
On both, water accumulated, which remained on Earth in oceans, but on Venus was lost to space.
And while carbon dioxide is fixed in carbonate rocks on Earth, it makes up most of the atmosphere on Venus.
