These aren't Warhol's boxes
Anyone who combines the terms Sweden and wooden box thinks of Ikea, but not of Andy Warhol.
Or is it?
Currently manufactured wooden boxes in Sweden cast dark shadows on Warhol’s work directory.
The majority of the ninety-four "Stockholm" Brillo boxes listed there are counterfeit.
After the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" a few months ago raised doubts about the authenticity of Andy Warhol's Brillo boxes of 1968, internal investigations at the Moderna Museet in Stockholm now come to a sobering conclusion: the six "Brillo-Boxes", which the former museum director Pontus Hultén gave to the Moderna Museet as a gift in 1995, are also copies of the "100th edition of the Art Boxes".
The prehistory is intertwined, a confusing combination of artistic and curatorial productions.
In 1964, Warhol created his first "Brillo boxes", painted wooden boxes based on the red-blue-white design of the cardboard boxes of the soap powder "Brillo".
An exhibition of his works in the Moderna Museet in 1968 exhibited - with Warhol's consent - hundreds of Brillo boxes made of cardboard: these (for cost reasons) did not come from Warhol, but were delivered directly from the Brillo Cartonage Factory.
It was not about works of art, but about their role models, about mere exhibits.
At the same time, Warhol probably granted permission in 1968 to have a few Brillo wooden boxes produced in Sweden, but they were not exhibited in the Moderna Museet.
Contemporaries now speak of around fifteen boxes, which at that time have rightly entered the art and auction history as authorized original Andy Warhol Brillo boxes with the name "Type Stockholm".
Some of them have earned more than $100,000 at auctions.
The problem now is that the legendary museum director Pontus Hultén later falsely claimed that around a hundred wooden crates had been produced and exhibited in Sweden in 1968, which Warhol then left to him.
In fact, Hultén’s 105 boxes were not produced until 1990 in Malmö for an exhibition in St. Petersburg.
At that time, Warhol had been dead for three years.
Lars Byström, chief conservator at the Moderna Museet, has investigated the six Brillo boxes owned by the museum, three of which were privately owned in Sweden, two of which were made in Stockholm in 1968: their press panels were first primed and trimmed, after which white oil paint was applied with a brush.
The structure of the copies from 1990, on the other hand, reveals that the paint with a paint roller without primer was applied directly to the press chipboard - in addition, it is not oil paint, but acrylic paint.
"These boxes were not authorized by the artist and should be removed from the official list of Andy Warhol's Brillo boxes," says the director of the Moderna Museet, Lars Nittve, "if the 'Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board' in New York does not come to any other conclusion, the Moderna Museet will classify the six boxes in its collection as copies/exhibition material."
In July, however, the Authentication Board announced that it would investigate the “severe accusations” made in the soap powder boxes.
Since then, however, they have been enveloped in relentless silence.
Rebellion in Manila
In the Philippines, rebel soldiers who entrenched themselves in a hotel in Manila and demanded the overthrow of President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo have given up.
He cannot be held responsible for bloodshed, the leader Antonio Trillanes, who accused the president of corruption and electoral fraud, told reporters at the hotel.
Government loyal soldiers had previously stormed the hotel under tear gas.
About two dozen soldiers had been entrenched in the building for hours.
About half of them were on trial on Thursday for a failed coup attempt in 2003 - among them Trillanes.
He used the trial to suddenly settle down with about 30 sympathizers.
The military police officers, who were supposed to guard him, had apparently run over to him and joined his mutiny.
They entered the Peninsula Hotel and demanded the overthrow of President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo.
Loyal government forces shut down the district around the prestigious hotel.
The President called for an urgent meeting of the Security Cabinet.
National security adviser Norberto Gonzales condemned the actions of the soldiers.
“People have enough,” Trillanes said.
“We call on people to join us.”
General Danilo Lim, who formerly commanded the elite Scout Rangers unit, said other army units wanted to join the march shortly.
Government critics called for large demonstrations against the president on Friday.
Their government has been overshadowed by corruption allegations for months.
Manila’s financial district was already the main scene of the attempted mutiny of around 200 military personnel against Arroyo in 2003.
The insurrection failed after just under 24 hours of refusal of the army to join.
Since 1986, there have been at least seven coup attempts against democratically elected governments in the Philippines.
